			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Guide to Battling</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:creelant@ucs.orst.edu">Ty Creelan</a> | 
		            8/19/1999 1:17:36 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Guide to Battling<BR>
:Message intercepted on an Orc Runner in the Butcherblock Hills:<BR>
<BR>
(Editor's Note: While Dragoon Ruddymane has provided this advice with reference to his own breed, (Cursed be they!) it has been found, upon analysis, to evince effective tactics for military endeavors and is thus deemed worthy to be entered into the annals of Felwithe. -High Lord Jyeel) <BR>
<BR>
Har! Greetings from Neriak. As a member of the Indigo Brotherhood, I often hear about how young dark elves have difficulty finding places to hunt, due to compeition with human offal and such. The way I and me many relations solved this problem, is by banding up with fighters of the same skill level as yerself in full groups and head into a dungeon (Mmm... I loves those kinds of dank and dreary places, I does.) which is a good circle of skill above any of you. You shall be fighting creatures which could shrive you in a glance if you were alone, but that's why yer grouped up.<BR>
	One thing some don't seem to realize is, as I once was learned, that the whole is greater than the sum of the parts. (I'll say that again.) The whole is greater than the sum of the parts. One magicker alone, one fighter alone, and a single priest often can stand up to a foe of their ability, but a *combination* of the three, acting together, can challenge an opponent of *more* than thrice their ability. While we fighters don't truck much with figures and scrolls, the aspiring swordmaster should realize this and strive to find companions when possible.<BR>
	So, as I says, get yerselves some bands together and go roving around in dungeon you'd never e'en thinks of fighting in otherwise. I must admit, this takes a bit of gall, but the winnings is great, for it is the growth of yer fighting experience at the greatest speed.<BR>
	Firsts off, make sure yer group has a clever elf heading the helm o'yer team. Don't let no trolls or ogres try to lead you, for their minds are as blunt as an old War Maul, brutes that they is. However, don't let no magickers captain yer team, either, fer the little snufflers will have their eyes in an old tome half the time, while yer team goes all to pieces, more oft than not. That means we warriors makes the best captainses. (And rogues, too, the sneaky sons of serpents, but no one on yer team will trust 'em, says I.) <BR>
	Yer team should also have a sentinel, some one to look out fer ghoulies and such whilst the others rest. One might think that with a team of a dozen or so such a watcher ain't needed, but they is. Many the time a ghost or skullerton has crept up on us unawares, and made all split. Most ogres and such be the look-out passing well, unless perchance those great snuffling noses get in way of their sight.<BR>
	Who to include in yer team? I take (when I can gets 'em) two warriors, three wizards or magicians, and a cleric on each team. Pure classes are generally more effective in a group, and are to be preferred, for jacks of all trades are masters of none. This should enable you to challenge opponents which earlier caused you to make water at the sight of. <BR>
	Fighting a foe one at a time is fairly simple and to be preferred. When fighting one foe, time is not as great of an issue and if the meditation of your magickers is properly arranged, your power shall increase with time whereas that of the single foe shall certainly decrease, especially if damage over time spells are used. Be wary that yer magickers cast their most powerful spells towards the middle of the fight and not the begining, or you'll have a bloody heap of robe before the battle has scarcely begun. Also have warriors hew the foe from opposing directions, making more damage to it.<BR>
	If you's is fighting a group of foes, have everyone target the strongest one and take it first, excepting the second warrior and priest, who's job it is to anger or soothe the others, taking in damage from those quarters. When fighting a group of foes, time is of the essence. The first foe should be dispatched quickly and with help from everyone. The team leader should identify the second target, before the first one is at 1/4 life. Ideally, the second foe to target is also the second strongest or most vital, but identifying any one is better than nothing. Furthermore, be sure to hew at the target foe from all directions as in single combat.<BR>
	1/4 of the way through the battle, the cleric should switch from fighting and absorbing damage to healing and meditating. The cleric should be careful at the start of the battle to avoid letting any creature target him, but as clerics do not club for very much power, this shouldn't be too hard. The cleric should rejoin the fray at the end of the battle only if needed, otherwise the cleric should continue meditating in order to administer heals after the battle.<BR>
	Warriors should toggle between 2H and 1H w/shield fighting during the battle as the situation warrants. 2H (slash) can be used to effect greater damage and more wrath from the opponent whereas 1H w/shield offers better armour and conserves stamina more readily. Generally, I start off with 2H (Upper levels, dual wield is option) and switch to the shield after the cleric begins the first meditation and arrange for the second warrior to do the opposite. Thus, while the second warrior is taking damage (1H), the first one is making damage(2H), and when the foe switches to the first warrior, their equipment if reversed.<BR>
	Magickers, and sundry wizardries. I know but little of this art, and shall say nought which was not already stated. <BR>
	I returned, and saw under the sun that the race is not to the swift, nor battle to the strong, neither yet riches to men of understanding, but time and chance happenth to them all.<BR>
<BR>
Transcribed by myself, Gilron, Sub-librarian and Priest of Innoruuk in the Royal Library.
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
				<td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td></tr>
